<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">one of which is the great danger of being cut off by an Enemy another when the Buffaloes approach the Villages in large herds a large party can surround and kill them all<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This way of hunting answers many good purposes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Dull horses share equally with good racers and nothing but bows and arrows are used on these occassions.  When a hunting excursion is in agitation among the mandanes the other Villages being informed the day is fixed, and they assemble in the rear of the Village then proceed in a body to look out for the Buffaloes.  When the party return the animals killed become common property and those who were not of the expedition are through civility generally the best served.  Old people who are destitute of relations to assist them in their wants crawl out of the Villages to receive charity and the hunters who are natur<span class="DelHand-author">ly</span><span class="AddHand-author">ally</span> generous commonly allow the poor creatures an ample share.  The Villages at a distance have the resemblance of mole hills or muskrat cabins<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The houses are placed in a circular line enclosing a vacant space of about four acres in Superficies and which forms the </p>

